<br>
On the other hand, the sohei, the warrior monks of Japan, might be able to be.  As might the monk who, using a short staff, was the only one known in written history to defeat Musashi in a duel (after which Musashi spent like a year at the monestary studying the short staff from the monk).<br>
<br>
Another from Japanese history who could probably be considered as having the paladin ideal is Morehei Ueshiba, the founder of Aikido.  He was clearly a skilled warrior, was vicious with a sword, yet was also a shinto priest who preached peace, love and harmony.  He believed tha violence was a failure to live in proper harmony with man and nature, and that the true nature of a warrior was not to hurt, injure or destroy, but to protect the weak and innocent from those who would prey upon them.  He believed that non-violent methods were best for this, and that fighting was a last resort, only after the failure of other methods.<br>
<br>
He also spoke against the Japanese attacking the US during WWII, feeling that it was morally wrong to do so.  The art he created, Aikido, gave the practicioner the option to use methods that wouldn't necessarily injure or kill your opponent.<br>
<br>
Although, thinking about it, he might be a monk instead.  It's hard to say...<br>
